       #include <strings.h>

       void bcopy(const void *b1, const void *b2, int length);

       int bcmp(const void *b1, const void *b2, int length);

       void bzero(void *b, int length);

DDeessccrriippttiioonn
       The  functions  bcopy, bcmp, and bzero operate on variable
       length strings of bytes.  They do not check for null bytes
       as the routines in and do.

       bcopy copies length bytes from string b1 to the string b2.
       Overlapping strings are handled correctly.

       bcmp compares the first length bytes  of  byte  string  b1
       against byte string b2, returning zero if they are identi-
       cal, 1 otherwise.  Both strings are assumed to  be  length
       bytes  long.   bcmp  of  length  zero bytes always returns
       zero.

       bzero places length 0 bytes in the string b.

